animal.description:
Approximate Birthday: 10/31/2020

I'm a cute puppy! I'm still learning how to be an awesome dog for my new furever family!  I’m working on getting all my puppy shots and other vetting done. You can submit an application for me and then wait on the humans to review and email you back.

As a puppy, I am required to go to training within 90 days of my adoption with a certified trainer. Paws and Heels is recommended. 

What breed am I? Mixed mutt! ODHS does not breed label (unless there’s official paperwork), as studies show it is nearly impossible to tell the exact breed of each dog based off of their appearance.

Educational article:
3/3/3 Rule;
https://www.rescuedogs101.com/bringing-new-dog-home-3-3-3-rule/?fbclid=IwAR2iv5m7fqk3FieO7LOsstGeGsYYV_F1rJOd1BPxaImofLpcinpYsUbFRWs

Adoption Donations are $250 for an adult, $350 for puppies (a dog under one year of age), and $125 for a senior dog (based on the age of the dog). Adoption donations are to be made via cash, and credit/debit card. There is a $5 fee to run cards.

Please remember to bring a collar and leash (non-retractable) with you the day of the adoption. Note: Martingale collars and slip leads are strongly recommended.

Due to COVID19, we aren't having as many open, public adoption events.  Current schedule is pre-determined meet and greet appointments are Wednesday evenings and on Saturdays.
Our adoption center is located at 3602 Lafayette Blvd, Suite 102, Fredericksburg, VA 22408. It's important that you keep an eye on your emails for any changes or updates during the adoption process.

Visit our website for an application to adopt. 
https://www.olddominionhumanesociety.org/adoption-application

Old Dominion Humane Society is a volunteer based organization. We are run completely by volunteers, who also have full time jobs, so we appreciate your patience.  Currently, the average timeframe for a response to your application is 1 week.

Like us on Facebook "Old Dominion Humane Society"
and be a part of promoting forever homes for dogs in need.
#Adopt #Donate #Foster #Volunteer 

Note: ODHS only adopts to Virginia and surrounding states (including D.C.). A $50 out of state fee applies.

animal.description:
Hello, my name is Baron. I am about 2 years old, male, german shepherd/labrador mix current on vaccinations -rabies, distemper/parvo, dewormed, neutered. 

Baron was original found on a side of a road and he was very happy with his family, but their living conditions changed and they can't have him anymore. Baron grew up around children and cat, but he doesn't like other dogs. Given his food protective behavior, Baron would do best in a home without small children.

Baron is just the sweetest dog ever!! He loves to give kisses and He loves walks. Baron is a little shy at first but give him a couple of minutes and he is all loves and wants to play!

Adoption Fee $325
This tax-deductible fee pays for the vaccinations, spay/neuter, boarding, food, and overall care of all the animals at the shelter.

(*Includes spay or neuter with HHP vet. If a personal vet is preferred a partial refund will be issued. KEEP ONLY IF NOT FIXED)

**If you're unable to adopt, please consider donating or volunteering your time to these deserving animals currently living at HHP. They require care and love on a daily basis, which adds up monetarily. Our shelter is funded by donations and adoption fees alone. The need is great within our community and your support matters.

If you have questions, please stop by any day between 1pm-6pm. Contact our office at (406) 896-1700 or Angie (406) 860-8735.

animal.description:
Our Uhaul dog, came in with sister Dolly. 

Danny   
(5-7 years old)

LIKES:
Cookies/bones
Play time!
Walks/runs/ball play
Indestructible bones/antlers
Stuffed Kongs

DISLIKES:
Taking his treasures away

About me…..I’m a good -fun-bouncy-boy who just wants an active, & safe home. Very active! 
   
SCHEDULE & FOOD ROUTINE :
AM:  1c. quality dry food + ¼ can of quality wet food
PM: 1c. quality dry food + ¼ can of quality wet food
**“Fish Friday” – replace wet food with a can of sardines (in water) 
+ once a month sautéed beef liver ( lunch portion about 3 oz.)
+ organic yogurt + probiotics weekly

Details from Danny’s loving foster: This boy is a gorgeous medium size lab/dobie/sharpei/bully mix. Short haired boy, his fur is very soft. DNA test would be interesting!

A VERY active boy with LOTS of “puppy” energy! Would love a family that can take him on at least 3 walks a day, or be able to run in a fenced in yard, at least 6’, as he can jump!

He appreciates a variety of indestructible bones & toys, stuffed Kongs, and chewy kong balls, large antlers.  He is potty trained and is used to going out 4x a day for potty breaks. 

Danny is a mart and treat driven, I’m sure he would be easy to train for various activities, jobs, & tricks. He can sit, catch bones. He is working on giving up/sharing toys, leash manners & separation anxiety is improving. He patiently waits for his food 
bowl to be put down, we use a “slow feeder” because he used to gobble it down too fast.

Current Recommendation: Active home who can walk/run 3-4 times a day, or play in fenced in yard. Only pet, no kids due to activity/strength/manners & not being able to share treasures with other dogs.
He is learning quickly to trade his ball/toy for treats, but not likely to share with a dog.

animal.description:
Snow is a 2 yo, 40lb, female (spayed), mix breed. NKGC pulled her from our local animal control on November 7th 2020. At the time we pulled her, Snow was completely broken. She had been on a strict "Bite Quarantine" for over a month, that is with no human interaction at all. We tried to uncover the details surrounding the incident without success. She spent her days at animal control curled up in a corner trembling in terror. We had a dog trainer/ behaviorist come and evaluate Snow and his evaluation was that she is terrified, depressed, and traumatized. 

Once we took Snow into our care she went to and has been with her loving foster home ever since. We wanted to give Snow a safe place to decompress and learn that humans are not bad. She is now completely vetted and ready for her forever home. 

Her foster mom says, " she has done great with her other dogs and cats. She's fairly energetic and wants to play with the other pets of the house. She does not have much interest in toys. She loves treats and takes them very nicely. She loves getting to play in the back yard and then when she comes back in she loves to take a good nap. She will need a home with a secured fenced in yard. She is not an escape artist, she just loves to be outside and especially in the beginning when I had her she was checking for a place to get out, she doesnt do that anymore. Due to her trauma history and her background in general I think her ideal home would be an active home with another dog that she can play with, a home with no children, and someone who has the patience and is willing to accept Snow on her terms."

If you think you are the right person for Snow, please fill out an adoption application here: https://form.jotform.com/203216945213146

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Hi there, my name is Simba, I am 3. The rescue says I am an Australian Cattle dog. I had a rough start in life, but I am so happy to have another chance. I was abused when I was little and did not really learn to trust humans. This just made me super sad and scared of everything. But I just knew I was worth so much more. Then a nice human came along and adopted me. I had the best life. I know it wasn't my owners fault, but I had to be rehomed again because he got sick. I just try to remember, no matter what comes to me in life, I know I can always recover from it. I still face everyday challenges with changes. I need slow introductions to humans and time to warm up. But the impact I will have on your life, through trust and love, will be a very special bond. As long as I have my safe space like the crate, I will be happy. When I am not there, I like to explore the backyard, chase balls, and frisbees. I love playing in the water hose, pool, or sprinklers. I am bit of a homebody; new environments are scary to me, especially if there are strangers. I could probably warm up on a hike with just my people, but I don't want to go to soccer practice or brunch. I really struggle making new friends in a new environment, I am best doing this at home in my safe space with no walks. I just really enjoy my own yard with my own people. I do require a fenced yard. This is a must and will also help me to feel safe and allow me to run around and play! I am such a cuddle bug. REALLY smart because I will learn any new trick usually within a day. I am dog friendly but really like smaller dogs, ones that will help me build my confidence around the house. Just make sure you make room on your couch for snuggles, I will even let you pick the movie. Can't wait to meet you!

Simba is only available for adoption in TX.

All our dogs require secure VISIBLE fencing. Height dependent upon the dog.

All current pets in adoptive home must be spayed/neutered and up to date on vaccinations.

Adopter must be at least 21 years of age.

Adoption Fee: $400

All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped and up to date on vaccinations.

Adoption applications can be found on our website: www.connectionspetrescue.org

animal.description: Ygritte is a 1 1/2 year old American English Coonhound being fostered in San Antonio after being picked up as a stray.. She currently weighs about 53 pounds but would ideally weigh in the 60-65 lb range. She is housetrained but needs supervision in the house because she is a big curious puppy that is still learning what is and what isn't a dog toy. Ygritte does very well with her submissive foster brother and prefers to be in charge; she would thrive as an only dog or with another dog that will let her be the boss. She is food aggressive towards other dogs and needs to be fed separately. Ygritte would love an active family to take her jogging, hiking, or walking and is very affectionate with people. She should have a securely fenced yard since she has a strong prey drive and is determined to catch a squirrel or neighborhood cat.

animal.description:
Purvis and his siblings were born at Horse Creek on August 1, 2020. Their mother, Daisy, was rescued on June 9, 2020.  We were not aware that she was pregnant.  We are not sure who their fathers are, but all eight puppies are gorgeous!
 
Purvis is one of six boys.  He is friendly and playful.  He and his siblings, Qford, Umphrey, and Verge, favor so much it is hard to tell them apart!    He and his siblings have been lovingly cared for from birth and are going to make great family pets.  They are all extremely friendly and have never had a bad day.  They love people and love to romp and play in the grass.  

Purvis will make the perfect companion for a family that will give him lots of love.  He is ready to run and play and take long naps in someone’s lap! 

All of our dogs are spayed or neutered and current on all vaccinations. They receive monthly heartworm and flea/tick prevention. All of their medical needs are taken care of before they are available for adoption. Our adoption fee is $100.00. Please complete an application, if you have found a dog you are interested in adopting. You can find our application at www.horsecreekwildlife.org/applic.html. Once completed, you can forward it to adoptions@horsecreekwildlife.org or fax it to 731-926-3000. Kim Austin, our adoption facilitator, will be in contact with you as soon as she has an opportunity to review your application. Understand that she has other duties and she will not ignore any interest shown in adopting one of our dogs. An application will need to be approved before a scheduled time to visit our dogs will be set up.  It may take up to 48 hours before she returns your call or responds to your email, due to work schedules, holidays and adoption events. We do the very best we can for the dogs we have rescued and do not take the adoption process lightly. Please be patient and understand that we will place our rescued dogs in the very best homes possible and reserve the right to refuse applications.

animal.description: Beautiful Sadie is a 1 year old Bloodhound mix waiting in Mobile for a new home. Tall and weighing in at 74 lbs, she is housetrained, cratetrained, and knows basic commands. Sadie is very people-oriented and doesn't do well with other dogs or cats, and she has never been around small children. She is trained to eat in her kennel and runs to it at feeding time. Sadie is energetic outside and loves to run and play fetch; she will even throw the ball for herself if you take too long! Once she comes inside, she transforms into a couch potato and just hang out with her people. She is the goofiest dog and will never fail to make you laugh. Sadie absolutely loves car rides and sticking her head out of the window. Sadie loves toys but needs the tough ones. Sadie is fine left alone in the house for short periods of time with proper toys, but at her age can't yet be left alone too long or she can be mischievous. She walks well on a leash. She is very expressive and vocal - she sings songs of joy when she sees her people and grunts with displeasure when you want her to move. She loves baths, enjoys swimming, and hiking. She lets you trim her nails with barely any effort.

animal.description:
Thank You DelleBovi Family!
Flynn Flat Bread was born about October 4, 2014 and weighs about 22 lbs. He is as cute as they come and was released from his puppy making days in a puppy mill in West Virginia. The 'millers' made a call to the humane society and said they no longer needed the services of 29 dogs and would they take them. The shelter is a kill shelter due to space and could not handle so many dogs and so they asked if we would take them. How could we not! So, we squeezed and adjusted and were able to take them all. Sadly, Flynn has failed two adoptions as after a decent length of time they still could not touch him nor would he stay in the same room as them. He is wonderful with the other dogs here and is now considered a Joyful Rescues Sanctuary pet. He can seldom be touched and if he is it is not for long and when we must 'catch' him to be groomed we must use a towel to protect our hands. He does happily live inside the house with the humans who live and work here as long as they are not forcing themselves on him, which we do not unless absolutely necessary such as hair trimming. It is felt Flynn is living his best life right where he is and is a very happy boy. From Dr. Rasnake: There is mild pegmentary keratitis which is likely from hair rubbing on the surface of the eye. This condition may be the result of improper hygiene/grooming. His future family will need to be diligent to keep hair cut short around his eyes so this does not worsen. He still can see, but there is some cloudiness.

Joyful Rescues has no funding except for our adoption fees and miscellaneous donations. Pet care and vet bills are expensive - you must be ready to take on this financial (as well as emotional) responsibility.
Can't Adopt Me? SPONSOR ME
Look for the Link 'Special Instructions to Seller' if you want to note a particular pet
Before you seek to adopt a pet from Joyful Rescues, please read our Pet Adoption page http://www.joyfulrescues.org/pet_adoption.html.

animal.description:
Sammy is a 25lb, 14 year old Terrier mix. We were told she was 14, but honestly Sammy still acts like a puppy somtimes, so we wonder if she is younger, but thats what we were told, so we will stick with that.

Sammy is the cutest, sweetest little girl. She gets along well with other dogs, loves to play with other dogs, and LOVES her toys more than anything. She enjoys snuggling and sleeping on the couch, which is where she spends most of her time. She also loves to drag her blanket around the house to snuggle on it where she wants....it's adorable. We would love to Sammy to go to a home with someone who has lots of time to spend with her, will spoil her rotten, and understands that she is a bit older. Right now she is totally healthy and happy. Sammy is also potty trained and listens very well. She will go to the back door at the fosters home when needing to go potty.

If you are interested in adding the sweetest older gal to your family, please fill out our adoption application at brighterdaysdogrescue.com

animal.description:
Please say hi to sweet Roo! Roo is a love bug who loves nothing more than to snuggle with her person. She's an older dog, so is calm and easy to be around. Roo loves to go on walks, car rides and where ever you'd like to take her - your perfect day is her perfect day. Well, more accurately, being with you is her perfect day. :-)

Being an older gal, she's has some "baggage" (don't we all): she's not crazy about other dogs (prefers keeping you to herself) and has a kidney condition which can be controlled by diet. Easy peasy.

If you'd like to know more about Roo, please fill out an application at www.richardsonhumanesociety.com and a counselor will be in touch!

If you are reading this, we are still accepting applications on this pet. 

Our Adoption Process:


	Meet the Adoption Criteria. Before you do anything else, make sure you meet our adoption criteria. You must be at least 21 years old. You must live within a 60-mile radius of Richardson, Texas. You must share veterinary records for all pets currently in your home and all pets owned in the last five years. All pets in the home must be spayed or neutered. If you rent your home, you must provide verification that pets are allowed on the property. You must be willing to be interviewed by an adoption counselor and you must undergo an in person or virtual home visit from an RHS representative.
	Complete Application. https://www.richardsonhumanesociety.org/adopt/
	Phone Interview. Compatible applicants will be forwarded to a counselor who will contact the applicant for a phone interview.
	Home Visit. If all the steps above are completed satisfactorily, we will set up a visit where you can meet the pet you are interested in. We will try to include the foster parent so you can learn more about how the pet is in a home environment.
	Complete Adoption. If all feel it is a good match, we will schedule the adoption at your home or an off-site location. The applicant will need to complete the adoption contract and pay the adoption fee. Our adoption fee is $250 for adult dogs, $300 for puppies (under 1 year) and $125 for cats. Discounts are available for senior-aged pets.


RHS adopts within 60 miles of Richardson, TX. For information about our adoption process, visit: https://www.richardsonhumanesociety.org/adopt/#process. If you are interested in meeting this pet, please fill out an application here: https://www.richardsonhumanesociety.org/adopt/

IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING PLEASE CONTACT PIKE PET PALS ON FACEBOOK TO SET UP AN APPOINTMENT. IF "PENDING" IS BY THE DOG'S NAME IT MEANS THE DOG AS A PENDING ADOPTER APPOINTMENT.

This dog is 5-6 years old, weighs 50-60 pounds and available for 1/8/2021

This dog has been wormed for roundworms and hookworms and vaccinated with a 5 way vaccination on 1/8/2021

This dog has been vaccinated for rabies on 1/8/2021

This dog has received a flea and tick treatment on 1/8/2021

Altered? NO

Microchip found? NO

How dog arrived at the pound: Found as a stray

Pike Pet Pals assists in helping dogs get out of the Pike County Pound. Private adopters can visit the Pike County Dog Pound at 2575 Alma Omega Road Waverly, Ohio from 10am-2pmMonday through Friday. Saturday and Sundays by appointment. We recommend calling ahead to make sure the deputy on duty is not on an emergency call. 740-947-5996

Rescues can contact Volunteer Julie at pikepetpals@gmail.com . For the fastest response please message us on our Pike Pet Pals Facebook page. Please visit our website at www.pikedogs.petfinder.com for information on adoptions.

Adoption fee is $50.00 cash. This fee includes a Rabies vaccination, 5 in 1 vaccination, worming for roundworms and hookworms, Capstar, flea and tick treatment and a current Ohio dog license.

Dogs are vetted at the dog pound. We do not guarantee a dog's health. Please take your newly adopted dog to a veterinarian as soon as possible. If you do not have a regular veterinarian we -recommend Chillicothe Animal Clinic, 1100 Eastern Avenue, Chillicothe, Ohio 45601, 740-773-4133

To donate for vetting and vaccinations please click on the Sponsor Me link. All donations are used for emergency vetting, routine vet work and vaccinations for the dogs housed at the Pike County Dog Pound.

animal.description:
Please note donations using the SPONSOR ME tab will not go to Fluffy Dog Rescue.

To Locate Our Application go to http://rescue.fluffydog.net/how-to-adopt.html

Our listings are updated throughout the day. If there is an applicant, it will say PENDING ADOPTION next to the dog's name. If not, please submit an Application that can be found on our site, www.fluffydog.net. 

MY AGE: approx.  16 weeks (1/27) WEIGHT: approx. 11 lbs. (1/6) WHERE I AM FROM: AL (arrival 1/2) 

MY STORY: Galena is like a little bear cub. She is really a lot fluffier than she looks in her photos. If I had to pick I would say she is the calmest pup that we have, but pups will be pups, so not sure any of them are that calm. 

I did notice today while taking photos that her hear is a bit crooked. Not sure if it is her ears that make her look that way, or the difference in her eyes, but either way it's unique and doesn't affect her one bit.

Dogs needing foster homes are available for adoption This dog does need a foster home. Have you ever considered fostering a dog?  For more information, see the Fluffy dog rescue home page. This dog does shed and is not hypoallergenic.

HOUSEBROKEN?   GOOD WITH DOGS?  Yes  GOOD WITH CATS?unknown

ADOPTION FEE: $550

To adopt the FIRST STEP is to complete an APPLICATION. The application can be found on our site www.fluffydog.net, or by clicking on the purple Fluffy Dog Rescue wording found in the left corner of this page under the dogs name.

Our dogs are located in foster homes throughout the state. We do not have a facility. Adopters must be 24 years old.We can not adopt to families with children under the age of six. We also adopt in WI, IL, and parts of MN. Most of our dogs are strays, so the breed is our best guess.
WI License #270548.
 
Check out Fluffy Dog Wellness on our Home Page. Great Solutions to Enhance Your Pet's Health. www.fluffydog.net

animal.description:
Hw+TJ just arrived at our shelter in September 2020, and he is already showing us so much of his winning personality! He's a flirt with all of our staff members and loves nothing more than to be with his people. His ears stand straight up on his head and he is so speedy! He looks like a big intimidating dog, but he's only about 50 pounds and he's full of nothing but love.

TJ needs to be an only pet in a house with no dogs or cats. We think he would do well with older kids! He just doesn't know his own strength, bless his heart. TJ's 4 years old. His adoption fee is $195, and he is neutered, microchipped, heartworm tested and current on all vaccines.

If you are interested in adopting please go to our website at www.partnersforpetsil.org and fill out an online application.

Adoptions are held at the O'Fallon, IL PetSmart every Saturday of the month from 11am-3:30pm and at the Glen Carbon, IL PetSmart every Sunday from 11am-3:30pm. We are also at Petco in Edwardsville Crossing on Sundays from 11:30-3:30 pm. The cats are only at Glen Carbon Petsmart. Please let us know if you are interested in a pet and we can arrange to have them meet you at one of the adoption events.

animal.description:
Name: Hyacinth
Suspected Breed(s): Beagle
Gender: Female
Age: ~1 year old
Weight: 20 lbs
Personality: Goofy, energetic, a snuggler, smart, funny, shy, quiet, affectionate, a quick learner, loyal, gentle, adaptable, eager to please, and playful. 
Observations with Dogs: Good with other dogs. 
Observations with Cats: Unknown
Observations with Kids: Afraid of children.
House Training Progress: In progress she still has very puppy-ish manners. 
Crate Training Progress: Hyacinth enjoys the crate!
Rescued From: Columbus County, NC
Additional Information: Hyacinth is one of the most adorable and goofy pups you will ever meet! She's a good-natured snuggler who is spunky and up for anything. Hyacinth is a big fan of playing with other dogs at the dog park and zooming around. She is still learning what is and is not a toy to chew on, but its hard to be upset, as she is so funny and entertaining. Hyacinth loves to curl up on the couch with her person, though she is working on feeling comfortable with men. She is a wonderful girl in search of an adopter who will patiently train her and give her the love she deserves.

Hyacinth and Haylin are sisters, but we do no adopt siblings together. 

__________________________________

If you are interested in meeting a dog or cat, we require an adoption application. If the animal has "HAS APPLICATION" listed, they are still available to receive additional applications but also may be in the process of being adopted soon. Apply for a DOG: http://www.citydogsrescuedc.org/adoptable-dogs.html

Interested in saving more lives? Foster a dog today! Learn more, see our list of dogs needing foster, and apply, https://www.citydogsrescuedc.org/foster-a-city-dog.html

City Dogs Rescue & City Kitties is a foster-based rescue in Washington, DC. We do not have a shelter. We focus on local adoptions in DC and the metro area of Maryland and Virginia. CDR&CK has a thorough adoption process in order to find the best possible fit for each of our dogs and cats (we do not operate under a first-come, first served model).

Upon accepting a new cat or dog into the organization, we provide a basic vet visit that includes necessary vaccinations, disease screenings, deworming, microchips, and spay/neuter (unless specified). We do not provide a comprehensive medical exam prior to adoption. As a result, sickness, injury, and disability may exist unbeknownst to CDR&CK. City Dogs Rescue & City Kitties is not responsible for payment of any vet care, including known and unknown medical conditions once a cat or dog is adopted from us. 
Dog specific: Rabies, DHPP, Bordatella vaccines. They are tested for HW, Lyme, Ehrlichia, Anaplasmosis.

Most cats and dogs will have a house training accident in the initial days in their new home and we cannot guarantee any pet is housebroken or crate trained.

We also update our Facebook page daily with new cats and dogs.

animal.description:
Beeper is a sweet mellow little guy looking for an adult-only home possible with another dog. 
He must have a home without a lot of visitors or people coming and going, and ideally a single adult home as he is possessive of his person. NO APARTMENTS, HOMES IN BIG CITIES, ETC.

He is dog-friendly but takes a little more time to warm up to people. Very loving once he likes you, and will want to be with you all of the time. We are trying to find a home where Beeper will not have to be left alone for long periods of time. Beeper needs a home with someone who has a lot of cattle dog experience!

Foster notes: Beeper is such a sweetheart! He's smart and easy-going, is house trained and learned to use the dog door right away. He's playful and fun and also a mellow and cuddly companion once he trusts you. Beeper loves treats and toys and puts up with his feisty foster sister. He's a quick study and will learn new tricks easily. He's an absolute joy as long as you are the only one in the home!

The stray hold, at the Toccoa-Stephens County Humane Shelter, is 5 days. That allows owners a fair amount of time to come looking for their pets. On the sixth day, the animal becomes the property of the Toccoa-Stephens County Humane Shelter and is offered for adoption. An animal may be pre-adopted, however, if the owner comes forward, within the 5 day stray hold, the animal goes back to the owner. The adoption fee is refunded at that time.
TSCHS Adoption Procedure
Adoption Fees: Adoption fee includes spay or neuter, current (age appropriate) vaccinations, and a microchip.
Hours of Operation:
 Tues.-Saturday, 11-6

Pricing:
 Dogs $100 - Puppies $125
 Senior dogs $60
 Cats $60 - Kittens $75
 Senior Cats $30

Contact Information:
Toccoa-Stephens County Humane Shelter
1747 Scenic Dr.
Toccoa, GA 30577
Phone: 706 282 3275
Fax: 706 886 7358
Email: Info@TSCHS.org

Adoption process:
 Fill out an application
 Fill out a contract
 Pay the adoption fee
*Stray animals may be Pre-adopted before the stray hold is up. If an owner comes forward, the adoption fee is returned to the adopter. If the owner does not come forward, the animal is scheduled to be altered. When that is done, the pet can go home with the adopter.
Unfortunately, we are not able to hold animals without the adoption process being completed.
That includes the payment of the adoption fee. Adoptions are done on a first come, first served basis. Applications can be emailed and payment can be made via phone and at WWW.PayPal.me/TSCHS.
Otherwise we can not hold animals. After the adoption fee has been paid, arrangements will be made to have the pet altered. No pets leave without being altered. animal.description: Hi! My name’s Peanut and I’m a 12-year-old spayed female Rat Terrier Mix. My previous home had a major life adjustment occurring and they were no longer able to care for me, so I am now residing at Lucy Mackenzie for the time being. It’s an interesting change, to say the least, but I’m adjusting very well. I’m making friends with the wonderful staff here and going for walks with them is one of my favorite activities, especially after the beautiful snow falls. I might be a little on the older side, but I still have a lot of pep in my step, so don’t let my age fool you! My one wish is that my forever home is just around the corner, and is a loving, quiet refuge to spend my golden years basking in attention. If you’ve been looking for a sweet canine companion to fill your days with love, please call to learn more about me!

animal.description:
Thank You Barker Family!Pepper was born about May 15, 2015 and weighs about 50 lbs. She is a Joyful Rescues sanctuary pet because she arrived from the southern high kill shelter extremely fearful of humans, but she is wonderful with all the other dogs here. Pepper never found a home because she has a very fast bite response to any human that moves too fast around her or in any situation where she feels uncertain what the human may do - even to reach out and pet her. Every one here understands this and new humans in the house are told ahead of entering not to reach out to Pepper. With this understanding of her behavior she has been living here and will continue to live here happily. She enjoys the activity and the acreage playing with the other dogs and is welcome to stay as long as she lives.

Joyful Rescues has no funding except for our adoption fees and miscellaneous donations. Pet care and vet bills are expensive - you must be ready to take on this financial (as well as emotional) responsibility.

Can't Adopt Me? SPONSOR ME
Look for the Link 'Special Instructions to Seller' if you want to note a particular pet
Before you seek to adopt a pet from Joyful Rescues, please read our Pet Adoption page http://www.joyfulrescues.org/pet_adoption.html.

animal.description:
Meet Toby. This 1.5 year old male neutered husky is in need of your help. He has been coming into us as a frequent flier since he was just 9 months old. His owner did the right thing and signed him into us. This poor boy has had little to no proper training. Due to this he does not like to share his food with anyone and knows very few commands. He does know sit and overall walks nicely on a leash. He also has not been properly socialized with other dogs. On top of that he has problems with both of his hips and his knees. He needs a very special person or rescue to step up and to help him. If you are interested and you email us we will be happy to discuss what is actually going on with him. He is a sweet boy and really just wants someone to love him the way he deserves. 

If you are interested in adopting him please email us at animalshelter@islipny.gov. If you are a 501c3 rescue interested in pulling him, when you email us please include your 501c3 paperwork with the email.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Kenny wound up in a shelter late in 2020 because of an unfortunate incident. One day, the person who found him (and maybe was planning to keep him; we don't know) was walking him when Kenny tripped the finder, who fell on Kenny. Kenny responded with a couple of bites to the finder's forearm, drawing blood. The finder decided they didn't want Kenny and took him to the shelter. There, he turned out to be a good boy, loving other dogs and doing well with the people who handled him. But, because of the bite, only a rescue could get him out of the shelter.

So we did. He spent a little time in a foster, but because they were so far away from us, we brought him to our board and train. We learned while he was with the foster that Kenny likely was an outdoor dog, as he at first seemed uncomfortable inside the home. He also exhibited the excitement when walking that likely caused his finder to trip. Fortunately, our foster was aware of the incident and was cautious when walking him. We also learned that Kenny LOVES other dogs and wants to meet everyone he sees.

Kenny will need a home with an experienced dog owner who can help him learn to trust -- he is getting better and better with that, but is still somewhat leery -- and let him get comfortable on his terms. He's overall a sweet young dog we believe can lead a nice, happy life in the right home.
animal.name: Kenny

animal.description:
Betsy is a sweet, loving girl rescued from a high intake shelter in Memphis, TN. She is living in a foster home waiting for her forever family.

Betsy is one of the most happy, go lucky dogs in our home. She has played the companion dog to many of her foster brothers and sisters. She is our go to girl when introducing majority of the dogs, especially ones that are scared & uncertain. We believe Retriever can be found in Betsy's DNA because she loves water. She jumps in and out of the kiddie pool sometimes emerging her face in the water. She loves running and playing. 

Betsy is a special needs dog. Due to digestive problems, her preferred food is Pro Plan EN. We like to think of it as special food for a special girl.


If you are interested in one of our animals, please complete an application. The application link can be found on our Petfinder homepage under the picture. You may also find our application on our website at www.teammemphis.org under the Our Rescue page. If they are listed on our website, their adoptions have not been finalized yet. That does not mean that we have not received several applications, already. Please complete an application if you are interested and we will keep you apprised of their current status. We are all volunteers who work full-time jobs and have animals of our own, so please be patient with us. We will get back with you as quickly as possible.

animal.description:
Candy is a beautiful 8 month old, 45 lb Labrador Retriever/Great Pyrenees mix.
Candy is a super sweet puppy, and she is full of puppy energy. She is in need of a very special adopter because  she was born with a birth defect affecting her heart,  and it cannot be repaired with surgery.  We at Humane Tomorrow think she deserves to still find her forever home with an adopter who understands her condition will not improve but can be maintained with inexpensive medication. Due to this condition, she needs a home with a quiet, laid-back environment.  Candy likes other dogs, but she will do best as an only dog to help reduce her activity level. Candy is also good with kids, but all children in the home need to understand that she should not participate in activities like chasing a ball, running around the yard or activities where she overexerts herself.  She can still do lots of normal dog activities like snuggling with her people, learning new tricks, chewing on bones and toys and taking short leisurely walks.  With proper care and an enriching, loving environment, Candy could be a great companion for the right adopter.

animal.description:
Hello! I'm Thor! How are you doing today? I'm pretty good today! I have had some ups and downs lately but I'm keeping my chin up because who wants to be around a dog who is pouting. Not me, and probably not you either. Oh, you want to know what happened? Well, it's kind of a long story so I'll just give you the Cliff's Notes. 

I had a great owner. We loved each other immensely. Our bond was strong. Then he passed away and I was homeless. His son took me in, but after we lived together for awhile, his son decided that it caused him pain to take care of me because it made him think about his dad all the time. So his son brought me to the City Shelter. I guess I thought it might be a good thing to have a remembrance for someone you lost, but not for that guy. 

His loss. I'm a great dog! I love with my full heart. I like to have fun and I am a loyal companion. I'm feeling a little wonky from all of the transitions and loss I've had to endure, but now I'm here at Desert Haven and I am starting to feel stable and secure again. I am now ready to try again to find the next Love of My Life and if you are also ready, we should meet. See you soon! Love, Thor

(Thor is around 60 pounds)

animal.description:
Memphis

Memphis is a 1-2 year old hound mix who came to us in November from a county shelter in, you guessed it, Memphis. Unbeknownst to us, Memphis was emaciated at 25 pounds (we thought he was a ‘mini hound’) and had a broken pelvis. With crate rest and proper nourishment, Memphis is now a healthy, curious and playful young hound. Memphis does very well with other dogs. Memphis has not been around cats or children. 
Like any young hound, Memphis will need ample attention and stimulation. Memphis has not been able to go for walks as crate rest was required to heal his broken pelvis. Memphis loves chew toys and tolerates his crate. Memphis would prefer an adopter who is home most of the time so that he can get ample love, play, attention, and exercise. 
Memphis will be available mid January once he recovers from his neuter surgery. Memphis can look a little grumpy due to his under bite - but he’s the least grumpy hound boy you’ve ever met! Memphis’s adoption fee is $275. If you are interested in Memphis please fill out an application at https://soazbeaglerescue.com or contact us with any questions.


This dog's adoption fee is a minimum $275.00 donation to help us save more dogs. Southern Arizona Beagle Rescue, SoAZBR is an all-volunteer group. One hundred percent of your donation is used for the care and treatment needy beagles. Your donation is 100% tax deductible, too.

We URGENTLY need fosters so we can help save more dogs.  If you can help, please contact us.

Southern Arizona Beagle Rescue Contact Info:
E-Mail Southern Arizona Beagle Rescue adoption@soazbeaglerescue.com
See more of our adoptable at Southern Arizona Beagle Rescue web site http://www.soazbeaglerescue.com 
Phone us at (520) 247-7720

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Snowbear and Tiger probably lived together their entire lives. They are bonded and must find a home together. We realize that placing two 13-year-old dogs together will take a very special person or family, but these two are sweet and have lots of life in them. They're healthy -- both just had dental cleanings -- and adorable. Snowbear has the short hair; Tiger's is longer. Their owner told the shelter they are American eskimo mixes. We aren't sure what mix(es) they are, but they sure are cuties!

They wound up at a shelter because their owner was evicted from their home. We couldn't say no to those sweet faces who had little to no chance of getting out alive, and when we told the shelter we wanted both they jumped at the chance, and they were out!

Snowbear and Tiger have plenty of pep, but they aren't going to run you ragged. They're happy to lounge and nap on a soft dog bed with one another as company. If you have it in your heart to open yourself to a couple of older gentlemen, ask to meet these two.

animal.description:
Blu is 5 years old, neutered, male Brittany with roan/white markings and, if I do say so myself, he is one very handsome lad! Both Blu and his mom Belle were saved from a bad situation that has left fearful impression on them. Both Blu and his mom Belle must be adopted together. He tries to stay away from the male people, and will often hide behind the skirts of the female humans to keep hidden from view. He is very scared when it comes to humans, but has a heart of gold and gets along very well with other dogs. Blu has not had any formal training, however he is quite accomplished at hunting squirrels and chipmunks, oh, and those house squirrels (cats) are one of my favorite things to chase! ! Blu loves to take walks with his Mom Belle, but he finds leashes a bit restraining, and whatever you do, don't allow Blue to get near an open door or gate! He wasn't named "Runaway Blu" at the kennel for nothing. Blu love car rides, and loads well and is quite well behaved in the car. He would do best in a home where there is a person home most of the day.

Foster parents: Blu is coming along with getting socialized, but still prefers solitude to being part of the family. He knows his name, but is still not quite ready to come when called, so some gentle encouragement is needed to bring him in. Blu runs and hides in another room, preferring to be out of sight. He often sleeps in the crate even though the door is always left open. Neither dog has had any sort of basic training, sit, lay, etc., and their fear of people makes this tough to work on, as they think they are being scolded. A home with no other dogs and definitely no cats is preferred, as both dogs team up to hunt smaller animals like cats and squirrels, etc. Both dogs are very gentle around children, and have shown zero signs of aggression to anyone.

Blu will need a physically fenced yard to help keep him active and safe! He is up to date on all vetting, including vaccines, heartworm negative and microchipped. Blu and Belle are a bonded pair and as such MUST be adopted together. You MUST have a fenced in yard with lots of room to run.

If you think you might want to adopt both Blu and Belle, please consider filling out an application online at: https://nbran.org/adopt/adoption-application. After filing out an application please contact the coordinator for the State in which you reside. The contact information for the State Coordinators can be found at the following link: http://www.nbran.org/contacts.asp. Blu's adoption fee is $350.00 which will help NBRAN cover the vetting costs and other expenses associated with bringing Britts like Blu back to good health and readying them for adoption. Don't live in Michigan or close by, No Problem! NBRAN also has a wonderful transport team who will help bring Blu to his new family, up to 1400 miles with the adoptive family being responsible for the last 100 miles, at no additional fee. If you would like more information about Blue please email Georgene Norris at georgenenbran@yahoo.com Thank you!

Hi, my name is Belle. I am a 7 yr old spayed female Brittany with roan/white markings. I am hoping to find a forever home for myself and my socially challenged son, Blu. We were saved from a bad situation that has left fearful impressions on both Blu and me. Although I am still a bit shy around female people, I just adore my male persons, and follow them everywhere. Well, that is unless there are squirrels around, then all bets are off! I am quite happy with the company I have, and am sort of territorial. While I've not had any formal training, I have to say that I am quite accomplished at hunting squirrels and chipmunks, oh, and those house squirrels (cats) are one of my favorite things to chase!

I love to run, so I'll need a nice physically fenced in yard to romp and play in, and if there are squirrels, BONUS! I love to take walks, but find leashes a bit restraining. We love car rides, and load well and are quite well behaved in the car. I would do best in a home where there is a person home most of the day.

Foster parents: Belle runs in and makes herself at home on her bed. Neither dog has had any sort of basic training, sit, lay, etc., and their fear of people makes this tough to work on, as they think they are being scolded. A home with no other dogs and definitely no cats is preferred, as both dogs team up to hunt smaller animals like cats and squirrels, etc. Both dogs are very gentle around children, and have shown zero signs of aggression to anyone.

Belle will need a physically fenced yard to help keep her active and safe! She is up to date on all vetting, including vaccines, heartworm negative and microchipped. Belle and Blu are a bonded pair and as such MUST be adopted together. You MUST have a fenced in yard with lots of room to run.

If you think you might want to adopt both Belle and Blu, please consider filling out an application online at: https://nbran.org/adopt/adoption-application. After filing out an application please contact the coordinator for the State in which you reside. The contact information for the State Coordinators can be found at the following link: http://www.nbran.org/contacts.asp. Belle's adoption fee is $350.00 which will help NBRAN cover the vetting costs and other expenses associated with bringing Britts like Belle back to good health and readying them for adoption. Don't live in Michigan or close by, No Problem! NBRAN also has a wonderful transport team who will help bring Belle to her new family, up to 1400 miles with the adoptive family being responsible for the last 100 miles, at no additional fee. animal.description:
Creek is an extremely sweet boy. About 4 years old. He is young and loves to let out his youthful energy on walks. He is leash trained and knows a few other commands such as sit. He would need a large, secure yard with high fencing and plenty of room to have fun.
He is not yet available to be taken home because he needs to receive his boosters. But in the meantime you may come visit.
Please find our applications and valuable information under 'Adopt a dog'* on our website: *www.beaglesandbuddies.com* and email your application to beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Let us know your preference of appointment day/time and which dogs you are interested in and we will do our best to accommodate and email you the closest appointment available. Please allow us up to a week to get back to you. Most appointments will be Friday-Sunday, 10 am - 2 pm, for an hour.
*Note bring any other dog/s and the entire family to your meet and greet at B&B.* A complimentary training manual is included with each adoption, authored by terristeuben.com. Check out her website - she is fabulous!
B&B is glad to be open during the pandemic. We know the value and comfort of a loving pet companion and are doing our best to help the dogs and folks who need them. We update our website daily and are always rescuing, vetting, rehabilitating, socializing.
* We are accepting applications for volunteers to spend time with our dogs, hang out, sing/read to the shy ones, walk/toss ball with those who go to the playgrounds; cleaning, office work, gardening, and building/repair projects! *
Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

Please note: If you are viewing this profile anywhere other than Beagles & Buddies own website, you are not receiving full info. Visit info on pet here.

animal.description:
***COURTESY LISTING***
For more info about this dog, please contact person listed below.

Hi, I'm Bingo! I was rescued from the street 4 weeks ago here in Santa Fe. tx. I am a 2yr old Cattle dog mix, I weigh 55lbs, I was neutered, chipped and vaccinated on 12/13-2020. 

I am in need of a forever loving person or family who has a big yard or land, can spend lots of time with me daily (not kennel me all day or leave me in a backyard while they are gone long hours). I love to go for rides in any kind of vehicle this is my favorite thing to do! 

My new people would need to be able to train me or afford a trainer to learn with me as I am Deaf and need a little help. But I am extremely intelligent and I've picked up on hand signals really quickly! I know the "look at me" hand signal and will sit when I see it, I know both thumbs down to lay down, two jerks of the leash to come (but I have a hard time concentrating when animals are too close or people I am unsure of and I'm a little stubborn when my eyes are dead locked on something) foster mom shortens the leash when I do this and gets in front of me to maneuver me to go a different way as I am still learning. 

We don't know about cats as foster mom hasn't seen me around any in a home environment. I love to play with my foster mom's, nephew's juvenile pit and the little monster even tries to punk me and bite my face but it is funny to me!. I am protective like most all cattle dogs but I do love people if they love me. I could probably even be a working cattle dog with some training. I hear other deaf cattle dogs do! I love to sleep with you and will be your shadow wherever you go! 

Is there a special family or person out there just looking for someone like me? Let my foster mom know she is picky and wants me to have the best life I could ever ask for! *Small rehoming fee of $75* FOSTER MOM WILL TAKE ME BACK IF IT DOESN'T WORK OUT!! Not for unstable living conditions where I would be left behind, dumped or sent to a shelter! Only stable, responsible people need apply.

For more info contact 409-440-6791 or dh722646@gmail.com.

animal.description:
Hi! I'm Kelly! The first thing you should know about me is that I am a boy who loves to play. Another great thing to know about me is that I am also smart. This combination makes playing with me a lot of fun! I love to play fetch the most. When you squeak a toy to get my attention, the game is on! Here's how the game is best played: I sit nicely while waiting for you to throw the toy for me. You throw it and I very happily chase it down. Then I bring it right back to your feet and sit nicely again. Repeat as often as you like, because I love this game! 

What I love more than playing is having kind people in my life. I've had some not-kind people in my life before I arrived at Desert Haven and guess what!? Those not-kind people didn't feed me. It was awful and I am not at my healthy weight because of the mean behavior from those not-kind people. However. And this part is very important. The most important thing you should know about me is this: I am resilient! I don't dwell on it. It's behind me, and I'm the sort of chap that looks ahead! 

I am looking to the bright future I have ahead of me. I have my good energy, my happy personality, my love of people, and I have a great heart. My future looks bright and all it is missing is my new family to care for me, play with me, and want me. In return for kindness and love and family and home, I will give my people a deeper love that is beyond their wildest dreams. That's what resilient dogs do. Love, Kelly

(Kelly is around 12 pounds)

animal.description:
Moe is a sweet young boy. He is 1 to 2 years old, 18-20 lbs. He loves to play with our volunteers and with our other doggie buddies.
Please find our applications and valuable information under 'Adopt a dog'* on our website: *www.beaglesandbuddies.com* and email your application to beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Let us know your preference of appointment day/time and which dogs you are interested in and we will do our best to accommodate and email you the closest appointment available. Please allow us up to a week to get back to you. Most appointments will be Friday-Sunday, 10 am - 2 pm, for an hour.
*Note bring any other dog/s and the entire family to your meet and greet at B&B.* A complimentary training manual is included with each adoption, authored by terristeuben.com. Check out her website - she is fabulous!
B&B is glad to be open during the pandemic. We know the value and comfort of a loving pet companion and are doing our best to help the dogs and folks who need them. We update our website daily and are always rescuing, vetting, rehabilitating, socializing.
* We are accepting applications for volunteers to spend time with our dogs, hang out, sing/read to the shy ones, walk/toss ball with those who go to the playgrounds; cleaning, office work, gardening, and building/repair projects! *
Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

Please note: If you are viewing this profile anywhere other than Beagles & Buddies own website, you are not receiving full info. Visit info on pet here.

animal.description:
We're not sure why someone would wrap a little chihuahua mix in a blanket and leave him outside a recreation center in Philadelphia but that's how Benji came to us. Fortunately he was found the next morning, shivering and cold, by a kind and caring soul who brought him inside to warm up. She contacted one of our volunteers to ask for some help. There has been no luck in finding his owner. 
Our volunteer took him to a vet and had him checked out. Poor guy had fleas, a skin issue from the fleas, and was so skinny. He was treated for the fleas and has been on an oral steroid since that visit (decreasing doses) and his skin is improving. He has gained a couple pounds and when his steroid treatment is done, he will be neutered. The vet estimated him to be about 7 years old. We thought Benji was a little grumpy initially but it turns out he just takes a couple days to warm up to people! With some love and kindness this boy's personality is shining through!
Benji is super sweet, cuddly, loves cats, is dog friendly, and is such a good boy! The vet estimates he is about 7 years old. He is working on his housebreaking and is about 90% there and some of that may be related to the prednisone he is on for his skin.
Benji is up to date on his vaccines, and Lucky Dawg will have him neutered when he is off the prednisone. If you’re looking for a small dog please consider Benji! Please go to www.luckydawganimalrescue.com for an application.

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Hera. I’m estimated to be 2 years old. I am female Labrador and great pyranese mix.  I’m a big girl at 53 pounds, and I LOVE to play, run, and go walking. I’ve been getting along with all the other dogs at my foster moms house but I don’t seem to like cats much, I bark at them a lot so I’d be beat in a home without cats.  I was an owner surrender to a kill shelter in Louisiana.  We don’t know why my owners left me there because I love all the people I come in contact with and I love belly rubs and affection.  I would love to go on walks and hikes.  

Adoption fees details: 
Puppies - Adults $ 550, Seniors $375. These adoption rates include transport from Alexandria, Louisiana to designated New England adopter pick up locations and NE foster homes using either Rescue Road Trips, Pets LLC or CAFA Transport. If you do a search you will see that this is a very reasonable adoption fee and comparable to other rescues. Adoption fee breakdown:Adoption Fee:   $  365.00Transportation Fee:  $ 185.00MA and NH only--Quarantine fee if applicable:  $125.00

Medical details:
All our dogs are altered (spayed or neutered), DHLPP, rabies, Bordetella, Heartworm tested with negative test results, microchipped, treated for parasites and on monthly heartworm and flea and tick prevention. A health certificate is issued by a licensed Louisiana veterinarian.

Adoption details:  
In some instances, a meet and greet is not possible before adoption unless we have a foster home in New England available. Available for a Meeting confirms the dog is in a NE Foster home and available for a meeting in the city state provided.  Most times our dogs get adopted before a foster home becomes available - and if so, they go straight to adopters home. Foster parents talk to adopters and feel confident that this will be a match before our dogs are transported up. Also if by some chance it is not a match we have a safety net in place as we ask that adopters to let us know that it is not a match and we direct you to take the dog to a foster home or boarding kennel once that is arranged. If necessary, we will ask you to foster the dog until a foster home can be arranged. 
Transport details:Rescue Road Trips (rescueroadtrips.com), Pets LLC (petsllc.net) or CAFA Transport will deliver our precious pups on commercial rescue animal transport to designated locations.  The fee is 185.00 which IS INCLUDED in your adoption fee already.**Rescue Road Trips, was featured on The Today Show - view it at http://www.today.com/video/today/55034556#55034556

MA and NH RESIDENTS:
If you are a Massachusetts or New Hampshire residence, an additional fee of $125.00 will apply due to State quarantine fee requirements. If the dog is in a foster home in MA or NH, this fee will be added in the adoption fee regardless of where the adopters home is located making the total adoption fee $675.00 for puppies and adults $500.00 for Seniors, otherwise the full adoption fee for all other states is $550.00 for puppies and adults and $375.00 for seniors. This includes a 48 quarantine, recheck by a MA licensed veterinarian, and issued a MA health certificate.

Visit all our available dogs at www.cenlaallianceforanimals.comWe update and add dogs frequently.

We hope to help make a difference in a rescue dogs life into loving responsible homes.

I am available for adoption; however due to my breed my adoption will have to be facilitated through a rescue organization. Please see the front desk staff or contact the Shelter at (248) 858-1070 for more information.

Meet Sadie! Sweet Sadie came to live at the Shelter when her people moved and could not take her with them. Poor girl, was confused about the sudden change in her living environment. Sadie is adjusting and making good progress! She is currently working on her leash skills and trusting people that come to meet her. Sadie enjoyed her human siblings, in her former home; she was playful and gentle with them. Sadie likes to be brushed and cuddle with her people! She is friendly, does well with bathing and really looks forward to being apart of a home life, once again!

The following descriptions describe behaviors that were observed during testing and/or veterinary examination: Evaluated for temperament with 336533 (male), and 335976 (female). She was in heat at time of eval. excited and vocal with both dogs, but not in an aggressive manner. Was more interested in male than female.
She is a big, strong girl. Does not appear that she has had much training on a leash. does know commands sit and shake 1/8/2021

American Pit Bulls are a misunderstood breed; for this reason, we implore adopters to these beautiful dogs to be very vigilant in training and socialization. This breed is very energetic and will need daily exercise. Because of their strength and energy, apartment living may not be the best fit. This breed can be loving, loyal and very smart. 

The above behaviors and personality traits have been observed while at the Shelter. If this animal was relinquished, information is gathered from the owner regarding behavior. Our wonderful volunteers spend time with these animals and give input on behaviors and traits. However, this description may not be all inclusive to how this animal will act in a loving forever home. Introduction to established family pets should be slow and monitored always. The same goes for children and other family members. Adopting a pet is a big decision and should be thoughtful. We suggest researching different breeds to match traits and personalities to your lifestyle. When adopting a pet, please know that this pet will be with you for their lifetime; patience and consistency will make for a successful adoption. animal.description:
Mia ACCT-A-82116

Intake: Owner/Guardian Surrender (Aggression to Animals)
Age: 2Y
Sex: Female
Altered: Yes

VIDEOS--
Mia Knows Sit: https://youtu.be/AeOnARlTDto
Mia in Slow Mo: https://youtu.be/c5XrL5fVjVE

This animal is currently available from foster care through ACCT Philly's Adoptions Programs. This animal is not onsite. If the foster has not listed a personal email, contact foster@acctphilly.org to be put in touch with the foster. 

We encourage you to visit our shelter during our adoption hours to view our complete selection of available animals. In preparation for your visit, please make sure to visit http://www.acctphilly.org/adopt/ to review our adoption requirements, hours of operation, upcoming events, and more! 

Is this your missing pet? If you believe so, please make sure to follow the instructions listed at http://www.acctphilly.org/lostpet/ so that we can make sure that you are reunited as soon as possible!

Medical Observation: 
1/15 (Vet Check) -- Patient appears calm and currently does not display any signs of anxious behavior. She has not been on Trazodone since her intake on 1/08.
1/8 (Intake Exam)- No medical concerns listed. Fully vaccinated 
1/8 (Per Owner) -- she has sensitive skin, possibly contact dermatitis. allergic to metal, similar to eczema

Behavior Observation: 
1/11 (Per Staff)-- On morning walkthrough, Mia is stressed at front of kennel. She is hypersalivating, bouncing between both kennel walls and then standing with front paws on kennel door and barking with pupils dilated. Whenever a dog barks, she sprints to the other side of the kennel and then back. Cannot focus on assessor even when offering high value treats. Placing vet check for Trazadone. 
1/11 (Per Volunteer)--
Kennel Presentation---Aroused---Runs back and forth and begins barking when she sees leash. She is very excited to exit kennel and will let you leash her. Getting back into kennel was very challenging. Fixated on other dogs on way back to kennel and hard barked once back in kennel.
Leash Skills---Pulls Strongly On Leash---Pulls hard towards birds.
Handleability---Aroused/Allows all handling---Super high energy and wiggly. Seemed to really enjoy getting pets and affection but was also very overstimulated with sniffs/birds/toys
Tag---Engages in play---Very playful. Will play fetch but doesn't always bring ball back.
Toys---Gives up willingly---Doesn't take possession of toys. Seems too distracted by surroundings.
1/8 (Per Staff)-- Mia became over aroused and started lunging and hard barking when a dog entered the intake waiting room. Please keep your distance from other dogs when walking her. It took her a few minutes to compose herself after the dog left.
1/8 (Per Vet)-- BAR; FRIENDLY
1/8 (Per Owner) -- energetic, loving, adorable. she is always excited. She is aggressive towards other dogs and animals in general. She also is aggressive to children. Knows sit, stay, give me paw, give me kiss. On leash, pulls when she is excited but understands to stop when the handler tugs a bit. Owner that surrendered was Mia's third owner; owner that surrendered reported that Mia adapts to new homes and environments very easily.

BITE DETAILS:
1/8 (Per Owner) -- Mia bit a two year old on the head: The child did not need to go to the hospital, but she did get a good amount of hair out, this happened July 2020
 and bit a seven year old girl on the arm: she had to get three stitches. This was August 2020
She has also fought with a neighbors dog and a friend's dog, the dogs did not need medical attention

animal.description:
Pogo is living in a foster home. Submit an application from our website and then make an appointment to meet him.

Pogo is not eligible for foster and will be a straight adoption.

Age: ~6 years
Weight: ~10lbs
Housebroken: Needs to be on a strict schedule of about every 2-3 hours
Crate trained: Hasn't been crated, but has done well with a sectioned area when his foster is away
Dog sociability: Friendly! Lives with many dogs in his foster home and has been doing well. 
Cat sociability: Friendly! Lives with a cat in his foster home and has been doing well.
Kids: Unknown, but may do well with older kids/teenagers
Ideal home: A calm home that can continue to care for Pogo's ongoing medical needs (listed below). He'd love a home with easy access to outside for potty breaks and thick walls as he can be barky.

SSBC (Single Senior Black Chihuahua) looking for love and home cooked meals - meet Pogo! He enjoys longs naps, short walks, cuddling under the blankets, sharing his opinions and making sure he is heard. Dislikes cold weather, the hallmark channel, when dinner is served late, losing at bingo, and cilantro- ick! Pogo is a very good boy and does best when on a strict schedule for potty and eating. Trust us - he knows when it is time to eat! He will not miss a meal if he has anything to say about it (bork! bork!) He sleeps for most of the day. Wears a diaper to avoid accidents in the house but really the accidents are unavoidable because he can't help it as a senior guy. It takes him a little while to fully warm up to his person. He doesn't like being picked up by people he doesn't know. 

Pogo's adoption fee is sponsored thanks to a generous donor! He is neutered, up to date on core vaccines, microchipped and heartworm negative. Pogo has heart disease and will take Pimobendan lifelong. Recommend annual monitoring with regular vet and/or cardiologist as needed. Pogo has elevated liver values - he has a history of elevated liver enzymes, and has had an ultrasound to evaluate his liver. He takes Denamarin and Ursodiol to assist with liver function and should remain on this lifelong, and will need annual bloodwork monitoring with his vet, or as recommended. Pogo is a senior dog and may have additional underlying medical issues or needs that have not yet been diagnosed. All senior dogs are recommended to receive biannual wellness visits with your veterinarian to monitor for any changes to their health. 

***We are receiving a much higher than usual number of adoption applications. We ask that you please be patient and someone will be in touch via email within 72 hours. Please do not email us unless you have not received a response in 72 hours. Please only fill out one adoption application. ***

animal.description:
APPLY ON OUR ADOPTION APPLICATION AT LEADRESCUE.ORG. WE DO NOT ADOPT OUT OF STATE. WE ONLY ADOPT WITHIN ILLINOIS AND WITHIN 50 MILES OF DOWNTOWN CHICAGO.

Update: needs to be an only dog. Still needs a home with a secured 6 foot fence. Older children fine.

******************************************

I don’t want to give my dog up. But I don’t have a choice anymore.

Look at your dog. Imagine a time when there wasn’t that dog in your life. Can’t do it, right? It’s okay if you have tears streaming down your face as early as 10am. They are happy tears.

But for some families, they have to imagine their life without their beloved companion. Their tears are no longer happy. Their tears tell us how much this dog is loved and how much it hurts with this decision. Although LEAD takes in a lot of owner surrenders, we honestly feel bad when we get messaged about one because it means someone is about to do something they never expected. 
Archer has a beautiful life with his family. Originally found as a 13 week old puppy thrown out of a car on their family’s farm in Georgia, his family raised him from that day until now, 2 years later. He does phenomenal with dogs both large and small, fine with cats, loves his belly rubbed but definitely too serious of a dog for any face licks, playful, housebroken, and is a very friendly, headstrong boy. So where’s the need to rehome?

Without getting into too much detail about the family’s situation, Archer would do better in a home with older or no kids. He does not realize his 120 lb Great Pyrenees/Retriever frame and being that he is still young and boisterous, it’s just something this family home life can not accommodate anymore. With the family’s young kids, he can get kinda growly and separating them all day, everyday is causing multiple meltdowns and breakdowns. It’s not healthy for anyone’s mental health. They tried behavioral training, medications, even was able to fundraise $2,000 for board and train-the facility gave them even a 3rd week on them because they could see his potential. So don’t knock the family who is doing what is best for them and Archer by going through a rescue to find a more suitable home.

Archer is a good dog. If you know anything about Great Pyrs, they are probably one of the sweetest gentle giants but they can be very wary of strangers approaching your home. They bark A LOT. They bark when you don't want them to. They bark when they feel the urge. But they bark out of protection. Archer will legit plow through your window if his warning bark is not enough (he hasn't but you catch my drift). Even if the person is like across the street, nowhere near its family, the GP will keep an eye on that person and stay alert until that person is far, far away. This personality trait goes along with them being very bullheaded, so an adopter should be assertive, tolerant, and a little bit bullheaded as well. That being said, he would do best in a neighborhood with not too much commotion and with neighbors who enjoy having a dog on duty all the time. He can pretty much thrive in most types of households though consisting of older well behaved kids or no kids, a friendly pooch or two to hang out with, someone who wants to share an active, fun, but quiet lifestyle. He will roll over on his back after he is done greeting you at the door, hence the upside down photos for show. However he still needs work on not jumping on you when excited. I mean he will literally go through your legs while standing so you might be airlifted onto a pony not by your choice. And per request of his original owner, Archer must have a 6 foot fully fenced yard (the more land, the better) and no to the apartment life. No tie outs. No half-a** fence jobs. No living on the 38th floor. Do not, I repeat, apply if you are in this category.

There really is a lot to this dog, but I am cramming what I can so you get an overall idea of who Archer is. In the end, even though Archer will no longer get to reside with his original family, he will find joy with someone new. And we hope to keep his family smiling by sending them updates throughout the years of Archer's new life.

Oh shoot, one last thing. Archer's girlfriend is a garbage can. He humps that daily. I knew I was forgetting to mention something that could win people over. If interested in the world's greatest goofball and stubborn AF dog, please apply for Archer at leadrescue.org.

Gretchen is just about the sweetest dog ever! She enjoys the company of people and will put her head in your lap and look at you longingly. She also enjoys cuddling on the sofa or when you are going to bed. Gretchen lives with other dogs and has fit in well. She knows a few commands and walks well on leash with tail wagging. She loves to play fetch and will even sometimes bring the ball back! Gretchen seems to want to chase cats, so we recommend a cat-free home.

Gretchen is about 5 years old and has a long tail. She is a big gal, weighing in at about 60 lbs. She’s spayed, vaccinated, and microchipped. She tested negative for heartworms and is taking heartworm prevention. 

Thanks for considering a dog from Texas Cattle Dog Rescue! We place heelers all over the state of Texas.

If you're interested in one of our dogs, please first complete our adoption application. You can download it at www.texascattledogrescue.com/adopt.html. Our standard adoption fee is $250 +tax for adult dogs, $300 +tax for puppies. Our dogs will be spayed or neutered, vaccinated and heartworm tested before going to a new home. We conduct a home visit to help match up the right dog with the right owner. For more information, visit our website www.texascattledogrescue.com.  Email adopt@texascattledogrescue.com if you have questions.

animal.description:
Dino is a handsome, Lab/Pit mix male that lived outside his whole life and fortunately was discovered by an animal advocate. The Advocate stepped up to help Dino and his owner. He tested positive for heartworms, was treated, and now is heartworm negative. His owner did not want to give him up so the Advocate and animal lover asked the owner if she could hang out with Dino from time to time and give him baths. That lasted a whole year and then the owner was diagnosed with cancer and was willing to re-home Dino with the help of the Advocate who had been visiting for a year. This sweet boy recently had surgery on his back (can be seen in the image) to remove 7 growths that were all benign. He also had 14 teeth removed due to multiple tooth fractures. He still has half of his teeth and he is still able to use them to eat hard food. Dino was raised as a guard dog but he is a big softy about everything in life. He is shy for the first 10 seconds he meets you, but then he will be your best friend. Dino would do best in a home with other dogs that like to play. He is also good with children. He LOVES cuddling and wrestling on the floor with his human. He is house trained and can be left out by himself and is also crate trained.....but don't close the door. Dino craves lots of attention AND he also loves his nap time. He will be your companion and best friend. He has lived outside his whole life and now he is living inside and deserves a human that loves him enough to give him a warm cozy home to call his own. Dino is in Tennessee and can be transported northward or he can be adopted locally to Nashville area. If you are interested please email us at ccrtennessee@gmail.com

ADOPTION FEE REQUIRED. Contact ccrtennessee@gmail.com.
